Let's think step by step.  The area of a parallelogram is given by the product of its base and height. For the first parallelogram, the area is $18=(ad)(2c)=2ac(d)$. Because the left-hand side is even, the right-hand side must also be even, so $d$ is even. Letting $d=2D,$ the equation becomes $$\begin{equation*}
    18=2ac(2D)=4ac(D)
\end{equation*}$$or $ac(D)=9/2.$
For the second parallelogram, the area is $72=(ad)(2c)=2ac(d),$ so $ac(D)=36$. Dividing this into the previous equation yields

\begin{align*}
\frac{ac(D)}{ac(D)} &= \frac{36}{9/2}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 1 & = \frac{72}{9} = \frac{8}{1}.
\end{align*}

This is impossible, so there are no solutions to this system of equations. Thus, the desired quantity $\boxed{a+b+c+d}$ does not exist.
